<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n11123e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n11" href="#n11123e">N11 (VI.B.5)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n11all.htm#n11123e"> 123(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> dans les revolutions un nom / fait plus qu&apos;une armee</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">&hellip; on criait aux spectateurs dans la rue et aux fen&ecirc;tres: &ldquo;A bas les chapeaux! vive la Charte!&rdquo; et moi je r&eacute;pliquais: &ldquo;Oui, messieurs, vive la Charte! mais vive le Roi!&rdquo; On ne r&eacute;p&eacute;tait pas ce cri, mais il ne provoquait aucune col&egrave;re. Et voil&agrave; comme la partie &eacute;tait perdue! Tout pouvait encore s&apos;arranger, mais il ne fallait pr&eacute;senter au peuple que des hommes populaires: <mark>dans les r&eacute;volutions, un nom fait plus qu&apos;une arm&eacute;e</mark>. <br><font color="green">[they shouted to the spectators in the street and at the windows: &ldquo;Hats off! Up the Charter!&rdquo; and I retorted: &ldquo;Yes, gentlemen, up the Charter! but long live the King!&rdquo; This cry was not taken up, but it provoked no anger. And so the game was lost! All could have been put to rights again, but now only men of the people should have been put before the people: in revolutions a name can do more than an army.]</font> <small> Chateaubriand, <a name="CHBD" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CHBD"><cite title="source">&OElig;uvres choisies illustr&eacute;es</cite></a> (1912) III, <i> M&eacute;moires d&apos;Outre-tombe.</i> 146</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
